<br>
It forces me to play without people who say &quot;(( ooc I would love to group with you but my guild charter says I can't ))&quot;.<br>
<br>
And it's not like I was looking to group for phat lewtz or whatever... this is people I see roleplaying out loud (/say) and who intrigue me, so I try to get involved, but they can't cooperate with me in any way because of their guild charter, because I'm not &quot;evil&quot;.  Yes, evil, which is all about cooperation with like minded individuals, and would <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>never</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> do something advantageous for itself instead of following its principles.  (Well okay that's lawful/orderly evil, but still, it's limiting and it affects how I can play when you take away potential groupmates).<br>
<br>
My point - your strict, absolute rules about who your guildmates can and can't group with causes me a loss of potential fun by interacting with people who happened to pick a different race/class than me, in a way both they and I might find enjoyable.  It limits the story, like where I offered to hire them at a disgustingly high rate for their services, when I was really just looking for someone to keep me company for a while while working on a quest, and dabble a bit in roleplaying on FV.<br>
<br>
Basically, these peoples' guild charter  wrecked my fun.<br>
<br>
Also,<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Someone said the game would have all the same characters You would know who everyone waswhen you met them. That is wrong. Some races get choices. Gnomes. Humans. Half-elf. They get choices. Iksar, Dark Elfs, Trolls, Ogres, High Elfs, Wood Elfs. No Damn Choice.<br>
<br>
NO CHOICE!<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I think that was me that said that.  Yes, if we followed Verant's guidelines, it would be the same damned characters.  Oooh, another dark elf agnostic rogue!  Ooooh another dark elf shadowknight.  I wonder if this one will say Innoruuk every third word and talk about how strong his hate is, and show me the blackness of his heart.<br>
<br>
How boring.  Sure you have choice.<br>
<br>
I'm sooo sick of the same old evil.  You know, the evil that bands together to fight good, as if it's some sort of happy team that works together to fight those wacky lightbringers.  /yawn.<br>
<br>
What about the kind of evil that doesn't know it's evil.  The kind that pretends to be good, the kind that lies to itself and says it's good.<br>
<br>
Interesting evil is the priest who burns heretics over some point of text or procedure of religion, or for having an opinion differing from the holy writings about whether the sun revolves around the world, or the world around the sun.<br>
<br>
Interesting evil is the paladin who uses his position of authority to win fame, and only takes on tasks which are likely to result in glory and honors from people, not the unsung but important quest.  It's the paladin who smiles and receives praise, honors, is described as kind, gentle, caring, and protective, but then goes home and beats his squire silly if he forgets a task or makes a mistake.<br>
<br>
Interesting evil is the drunken wizard, who knows his drunkenness is hurting his friends and companions who rely on him, but who refuses to get help with his problem for selfish reasons, until one day, a recklessly cast spell nearly kills a companion.<br>
<br>
Interesting evil is the evil that knows it's evil, but only works with people considered &quot;good&quot; because it can get away with more while in their company... say a rogue who doesn't let anyone know she's a rogue, and uses her position of trust to embezzle and set up a network of spies for whatever purpose.<br>
<br>
Interesting evil is the evil that exploits good for its own gain.  Anyone read Ender's Shadow?  About the way Bean's gang's new bully uses adult sympathy for children to increase his status and that of his gang, in order to get into the soup kitchen?  That was interesting evil.  From another perspective, Bean was interesting evil, because he analyzed everything in terms of his own gains, and was willing to hurt others for those gains (like wanting to kill the bully in cold blood early on).<br>
<br>
Anyway, far be it from me to tell anyone how to roleplay, especially when I don't bother anymore, but if you want me to be interested, you'll disconnect &quot;evil&quot; or &quot;good&quot; from professions and races, and make it instead dependent on actions.<br>
<br>
The best RPing I've seen (I say best because it most made me want to get involved) wasn't on FV, it was on rodcet nife, in a guild where the roleplay was all about motives and actions, and not about &quot;dark elf, thus evil&quot; or &quot;paladin, thus good&quot;.  I'm sure there are plenty of examples on this server, too, and I haven't bothered to find them, but SOE's descriptions of the races, classes, and deities are totally boring, are stereotypes, and if we all followed them as &quot;rules&quot; (which they aren't, they're explanations and background material, such as you'd find in a player's handbook for a paper and pencil RPG really), you could predict a character's motives and actions almost exactly by knowing her race, class, and deity.  And because some races or classes have very resistricted deities, sometimes just knowledge of race and class is enough.<br>
<br>
How much richer a game would it be if you have more realistic and interesting types of evil, such as closetly-evil paladins who believe they are good, and so on?  Much richer, in my opinion.<br>
<br>
Anyway, rules which allow no room for interpretation, or the &quot;spirit of the rule&quot; just restrict possible stories.  You can't argue with that, it follows from what a rule is.  A rule guides behavior by stating unacceptable (or required) behaviors.  If someone encounters the rule, and it contradicts what they're trying to do with their story, if they follow the rule, they were restricted by it.  Why restrict needlessly?<br>
<br>
No offense to anyone who roleplays their race/class/deity &quot;by the book&quot;, but it's just not at all interesting to me, and when you require it of your guild via a charter or whatever, it restricts me too. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=caeona>Caeona</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.spacespider.net/emo/grouphug.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 603<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/11/03 5:19 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3826.topic&index=64>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Hm</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>No offense to anyone who roleplays their race/class/deity &quot;by the book&quot;, but it's just not at all interesting to me, and when you require it of your guild via a charter or whatever, it restricts me too.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
